# DOM SELECTORS, NodeList, HTMLCollection — COMPLETE NOTES

These notes are written in simple English so they can be revised even after a long time.

---

# 1. What is DOM?

DOM = Document Object Model.

When a browser opens HTML, it converts that HTML into a tree-like structure.
JavaScript can then access and change that structure.

Example:
- HTML gives the structure
- DOM is the live version of that structure inside the browser
- JavaScript uses DOM to read and change the page

---

# 2. Why do we need DOM selectors?

DOM selectors are used to find HTML elements in the page.

After finding an element, we can:
- change text
- change color
- change background
- add/remove classes
- attach events
- hide/show elements

So selectors are the bridge between HTML and JavaScript.

---

# 3. Main DOM selector methods

The most important ones are:

- `document.querySelector()`
- `document.querySelectorAll()`
- `document.getElementById()`
- `document.getElementsByClassName()`
- `document.getElementsByTagName()`

In this topic, the most important are:
- `querySelector()`
- `querySelectorAll()`
- `getElementsByClassName()`
- `getElementsByTagName()`

---

# 4. `querySelector()`

## Meaning
It selects the **first** matching element.

## Syntax
```js
document.querySelector("selector")
Example
<p class="msg">Hello</p>
<p class="msg">World</p>
const el = document.querySelector(".msg");
console.log(el);
Result

It selects only the first .msg.

Important points
Uses CSS selector syntax
Can select by:
tag: "li"
class: ".box"
id: "#title"
attribute: "[type='text']"
Use when

Use it when you want only one element.

5. querySelectorAll()
Meaning

It selects all matching elements.

Syntax
document.querySelectorAll("selector")
Example
<li>One</li>
<li>Two</li>
<li>Three</li>
const items = document.querySelectorAll("li");
console.log(items);
Result

It returns all <li> elements.

Important points
Returns a NodeList
Usually used when you want to loop over many elements
It is static
this means if you add a new matching element later, the old result does not update automatically
6. What is NodeList?

NodeList is a collection of DOM nodes.

It is not a real Array, but it behaves in a similar way.

Example:

const items = document.querySelectorAll("li");

You can do:

console.log(items[0]);
console.log(items.length);
Important facts about NodeList
It has .length
It supports index access like items[0]
It can use forEach()
It is often returned by querySelectorAll()
Very important

NodeList is usually static when returned by querySelectorAll().

That means:

If the page changes later, the NodeList does not automatically change
7. What is HTMLCollection?

HTMLCollection is also a collection of elements.

It is array-like, but not a real Array.

Example:

const items = document.getElementsByClassName("box");
Important facts about HTMLCollection
It is array-like
It has .length
It supports index access
It is usually live
Live means:

If elements are added or removed from the page, the collection updates automatically.

8. Static vs Live collection

This is one of the most important concepts.

Static

A static collection does not update automatically.

Example:

querySelectorAll() returns a static NodeList
Live

A live collection updates automatically when the DOM changes.

Example:

getElementsByClassName()
getElementsByTagName()
9. Difference between NodeList and HTMLCollection
NodeList
Usually returned by querySelectorAll()
Can use forEach()
Usually static
HTMLCollection
Usually returned by getElementsByClassName() and getElementsByTagName()
Live collection
Often converted to Array when needed
10. getElementsByClassName()
Meaning

Selects all elements having a given class name.

Example
const boxes = document.getElementsByClassName("box");
Important points
Returns HTMLCollection
Live collection
Good for class-based selection
Does not support all Array methods directly
11. getElementsByTagName()
Meaning

Selects all elements of a given tag name.

Example
const lists = document.getElementsByTagName("li");
Important points
Returns HTMLCollection
Live collection
Selects by tag name
12. Changing styles in JavaScript

To change CSS using JavaScript, use:

element.style.propertyName = "value";
Example
el.style.backgroundColor = "pink";
el.style.color = "white";
el.style.fontSize = "20px";
Important

Do NOT write:

el.backgroundColor = "pink";

That is wrong.

Correct:

el.style.backgroundColor = "pink";

Because CSS properties are inside the style object.

13. Example of styling one element
<li>Hello</li>
const item = document.querySelector("li");
item.style.backgroundColor = "pink";

This changes the background color of the first li.

14. Example of styling many elements with forEach()
<li>Apple</li>
<li>Banana</li>
<li>Mango</li>
const items = document.querySelectorAll("li");

items.forEach((item) => {
  item.style.backgroundColor = "blue";
});
What happens?

Every li gets blue background.

15. Why forEach() works with NodeList

querySelectorAll() returns a NodeList.

NodeList supports forEach().

That is why this works:

items.forEach((item) => {
  item.style.backgroundColor = "blue";
});
16. Why this common mistake fails

Wrong:

items.forEach((item) => {
  item.backgroundColor = "blue";
});

Why wrong?
Because backgroundColor is not a direct property of the element.

Correct:

items.forEach((item) => {
  item.style.backgroundColor = "blue";
});
17. innerText, textContent, innerHTML

These are very important for DOM work.

innerText

Shows visible text only.

Example:

el.innerText
textContent

Shows all text, including hidden text in many cases.

Example:

el.textContent
innerHTML

Gets or sets HTML inside the element.

Example:

el.innerHTML = "<b>Hello</b>";

This inserts HTML tags inside the element.

18. classList

classList helps you work with classes.

Example
el.classList.add("active");
el.classList.remove("active");
el.classList.toggle("active");
Why useful?

Because adding/removing classes is better than writing all styles directly in JavaScript.

19. Best practice: use classes for styling

Instead of:

el.style.backgroundColor = "pink";

Better:

el.classList.add("pink-bg");

And in CSS:

.pink-bg {
  background-color: pink;
}
Why?
Cleaner code
Easier to maintain
Better for large projects
