22. Very important comparison table
Method	Returns	First or All	Static or Live
querySelector()	Element or null	First	N/A
querySelectorAll()	NodeList	All	Static
getElementsByClassName()	HTMLCollection	All	Live
getElementsByTagName()	HTMLCollection	All	Live
23. When to use what?
Use querySelector()

When you need only one element.

Use querySelectorAll()

When you need many elements and want to loop through them.

Use getElementsByClassName()

When you want all elements of a class and do not mind live collection behavior.

Use getElementsByTagName()

When you want all tags of a specific type.

24. Common mistakes
Mistake 1
document.querySelectorAll("li").backgroundColor = "red";

Why wrong?
Because querySelectorAll() returns a collection, not one element.

Correct:

document.querySelectorAll("li").forEach((li) => {
  li.style.backgroundColor = "red";
});
Mistake 2
item.backgroundColor = "blue";

Correct:

item.style.backgroundColor = "blue";
Mistake 3

Using forEach() on HTMLCollection directly

Sometimes HTMLCollection does not behave like a real Array.
Use:

Array.from(collection).forEach(...)

Or use a loop.

25. Convert HTMLCollection to Array
const arr = Array.from(document.getElementsByClassName("box"));

Now arr is a real Array.

Then you can use:

arr.forEach(...)
arr.map(...)
arr.filter(...)
